== Change Picture Size (Obsolete 2.7) ==

In the code at lines 156 and 162, the user pictures are displayed with the syntax: <code>$OUTPUT->user_picture($user, array('size'=>16, 'alttext'=>false))</code>  The number after "size" is the size of the image in pixels.  You simply change this number to change the size of the displayed image. We changed this to "35", which is one of the default sizes in which the user pictures seem to be rendered.

== Display Employee Role ==

We also added code to display an employee's role, if applicable, after the user's name. In order to make this easily changeable and customizable, we added a custom field for employee role.  To do this, navigate to "Site Administration -> Users -> Accounts -> User profile fields" and create a new profile field of the type "Dropdown menu".  Make sure in the field settings this is NOT required and NOT visible. For the Menu options, leave one blank line (for users without an employee role), then list the different roles that you want displayed EXACTLY as you want them displayed in the block, for instance:

<pre>

(Admin)
(Adviser)
(Chef)
</pre>

For all employees who should have a role, you must manually change this new field to the correct setting or mass update the employee users with a CSV file.

In the code, you'll first add a line before line 162 (the line in which you edited the picture size) with a variable declaration:

<pre>$employee_role = $DB->get_record('user_info_data', array('userid'=>$user->id,'fieldid'=>'2'));</pre>

The database table "user_info_data" contains all custom fields, so edit the "fieldid" to match the custome field you just created. (These ids should be assigned in the order of creation, so in this example, "employee role" was the second custom field created.)

Now, you will edit the line where you changed the image size from this:

<pre>$this->content->text .= $OUTPUT->user_picture($user, array('size'=>35, 'alttext'=>false, 'link'=>false)) .$user->fullname.'</a></div>';</pre>

to this:

<pre>$this->content->text .= $OUTPUT->user_picture($user, array('size'=>35, 'alttext'=>false, 'link'=>false)) .$user->fullname.' '.$employee_role->data.'</a></div>';</pre>

The only difference is that after the "fullname" variable, you have appended a space and your employee role variable.

== Display Customizable Border (Obsolete 2.7) ==

If you want to display a border around each picture, you'll need a few extra additions.

First, after defining your "$employee_role" variable, make a new variable "$color" exual to a string of the hex code for a default border color:

<pre>$color = '#ccc';</pre>

After this, make a series of if and elseif statements to change the color. You can use the employee_role, or add other variables based on user fields (you'll need to define them as you did with employee role; non-custom profile fields will be located in a different database table).

<pre>
if ($employee_role->data == '(Admin)') { 
    $color = '#888'; 
}
elseif ($employee_role->data == '(Adviser)') { 
    $color = '#bb8c15'; 
}
elseif ($employee_role->data == '(Chef)') { 
    $color = '#ac151e'; 
}
</pre>

Now, edit the line where the picture is displayed:

<pre>
$this->content->text .= "<div style=\"float:left; width:35px; height:35px; border:2px solid $color\">"
    .$OUTPUT->user_picture($user, array('size'=>32, 'alttext'=>false, 'link'=>false)) .'</div>&nbsp;'
    .$user->fullname.' '.$employee_role->data.'</a><br><div>&nbsp;</div></div>';
</pre>

Notice that a "div" tag is added surrounding the "img" tag but not the student name. in the div style, the height and width should be the same as the image size (in this case, 35px).  After the end anchor tag, but before the final end "div", add a break and an un-styled div with a single non-breaking space inside (this ensures a gap between photos).

