== Essential Theme ==

In order to make custom text automatically translate when a user changes her language, you need to customize the main theme's language files.  These are located in the folder 'theme/''yourtheme''/lang'.  You will see a folder for each language that the theme has been translated into.  For instance, the 'en' folder contains the language file for English (in the UK).  Open the folder, and you will see a file called 'theme_''yourtheme''.php'.  Open this file for editing, and at the end we will add four new strings for our [[Additional_Menu_Items]]:

<pre>
$string['mygrades'] = 'Grades';
$string['myaccount'] = 'Account';
$string['userindex'] = 'User Index';
$string['courseindx'] = 'Course Index';
</pre>

Make the same change in the 'en_us' folder for United States English.  In the 'es' folder (Espanol), add the same code but translate the text in quotes:

<pre>
$string['mygrades'] = 'Calificaciones';
$string['myaccount'] = 'Cuenta';
$string['userindex'] = 'Índice de Usuario';
$string['courseindex'] = 'Índice de Cursos';
</pre>

We also have French set as a language on our home page, but our theme has not been translated into French!  That's ok; most of the items here are only for admins anyway.  You can simply copy the 'en' folder as 'fr' and modify the four strings we're using into French:

<pre>
$string['mygrades'] = 'Notes';
$string['myaccount'] = 'Compte';
$string['userindex'] = 'Indice de l\'utilisateur';
$string['courseindex'] = 'Indice des cours';
</pre>

Notice the slash in the third string.  This lets the PHP code know that this is an apostrophe, not a single quote, and is part of the string.  Normally, in PHP, we could just use double quotes instead of single quotes around the string, but for some reason, this does not seem to work in the language files.

== Snap Theme ==

Add the following string for to the English file in the snap theme (this is covered in [[Add_Message_to_Flip_Phone]]):

<pre>
$string['vertical-phone'] = 'Please turn your device sideways to view course contents.';
</pre>

[[Category:Outdated_Moodle_Changes]]
[[Category:Essential_Theme]]

With a quick theme edit, we can alter the breadcrumbs display so the course categories do not contain links.  This keeps the students off of '/course/index.php', which allows them to view courses they are not enrolled in. (Note that students can still directly navigate to this page if they know the link)

In the file 'theme/essential/renderers/core_renderer.php', find the navbar function beginning around line 34:

<pre>
    public function navbar()
    {
        $breadcrumbstyle = theme_essential_get_setting('breadcrumbstyle');
        if ($breadcrumbstyle) {
            if ($breadcrumbstyle == '4') {
                $breadcrumbstyle = '1'; // Fancy style with no collapse.
            }
            $breadcrumbs = html_writer::start_tag('ul', array('class' => "breadcrumb style$breadcrumbstyle"));
            $index = 1;
            foreach ($this->page->navbar->get_items() as $item) {
                $item->hideicon = true;
                $breadcrumbs .= html_writer::tag('li', $this->render($item), array('style' => 'z-index:' . (100 - $index) . ';'));
                $index += 1;
            }
            $breadcrumbs .= html_writer::end_tag('ul');//$this->render($item)
        } else {
            $breadcrumbs = html_writer::tag('p', '&nbsp;');
        }
        return $breadcrumbs;
    }
</pre>

You'll want to edit the code within the foreach loop.  Replace the snippit:

<pre>
        $breadcrumbs .= html_writer::tag('li', $this->render($item), array('style' => 'z-index:' . (100 - $index) . ';'));
</pre>

with this:

<pre>
	if ($item->type == 10){
		$breadcrumbs .= html_writer::tag('li', $item->text, array('style' => 'z-index:' . (100 - $index) . ';'));
	} else {
                $breadcrumbs .= html_writer::tag('li', $this->render($item), array('style' => 'z-index:' . (100 - $index) . ';'));
	}
</pre>

$item-type 10 corresponds to categories, which by default link to '/course/index.php'  For all items of this type, we are printing just the category name ($item->text), not the full link.  The else statement uses the normal function for all other types of items.

